</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>AB2441:v99#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="AB2441"/><meta name="dc:title" content="AB &#xA;              2441-&#xA;                INTRODUCED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td align="center"/></tr></tbody></table></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><font size="3" style="FONT-FAMILY: MinionPC, Arial Unicode MS">
                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Assembly Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 2441</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Assembly Member Celeste Rodriguez<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 20, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> An act to add Article 7 (commencing with Section 18974) to Chapter 11 of Part 6 of Division 9 of, and to repeal Section 18974.1 of, the Welfare and Institutions Code, relating to children. </span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">AB 2441, as introduced, Celeste Rodriguez.
                          Community Supporting Innovation Pilot Program.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law establishes the Office of Child Abuse Prevention in the State Department of Social Services. Existing law requires the office to use certain funds to undertake specified activities, including, among other things, supporting coordination and sharing of best practices implemented by family resource centers with other agencies, when the best practices reflect strategies and outcomes that were achieved and supported by evidence-informed programs and data.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require the Office of Child Abuse Prevention to establish the Community Supporting Innovation Pilot Program to assess and demonstrate the effectiveness of community-based organizations, including family resource centers, serving as resource and referral avenues and alternative support pathways for families with complex needs or multiple stressors, or who are navigating
		significant barriers, but whose children are not at substantial risk of suffering serious physical harm or illness. The bill would require organizations wishing to participate in the pilot program to submit an application that demonstrates that the organization meets certain criteria, including, among others things, that the organization has the commitment of at least one partnering school district, hospital, clinic, or law enforcement agency that will refer potentially eligible families to the organization. The bill would require the office to select 25 organizations to receive grants to operate community pathway teams and provide related training. The bill would require a community pathway pilot site to receive referrals of the families described above and provide assistance to referred families navigating services related to basic needs, childcare access, behavioral health coordination, financial stability, benefits continuity, and other supports that stabilize families and reduce unnecessary involvement
		in the child welfare system. The bill would require the an evaluation of the pilot program and require the office, based on that evaluation, to submit a report to the Legislature no later than July 1, 2030, that provides recommendations for statewide implementation.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would also require the office to establish an internal unit of least 3 staff positions to oversee the pilot and would authorize the office to contract with a nonprofit organization to undertake certain tasks related to the pilot program, such as developing and implementing outreach materials.</div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">YES</span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.8541518648482823"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SECTION 1.</h3> Article 7 (commencing with Section 18974) is added to Chapter 11 of Part 6 of Division 9 of the Welfare and Institutions Code, to read:</div><div><div><div id="id_E201BEC0-AEAE-4144-91AF-1BC025E32A1E"><div><h5 style="text-align:left;">
                Article
               7. Community Supporting Innovation Pilot Program</h5></div></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">18974.</h6> (a) The Office of Child Abuse Prevention shall establish the Community Supporting Innovation Pilot Program to assess and demonstrate the effectiveness of community-based organizations, including, but not limited to, family resource centers, serving as resource and referral avenues and alternative support pathways for families with complex needs or multiple stressors, or who are navigating significant barriers, but whose children are not at substantial risk of suffering serious physical harm or illness.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) The pilot program established pursuant to subdivision (a) shall, at a minimum, include all of the following components:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) An application from community-based organizations
					 wishing to participate. In order to participate, a community-based organization shall be required to satisfy all of the following and demonstrate that satisfaction in the application:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) At the time of application, provide the services described in subdivision (g) of Section 18951.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Have the commitment of at least one partnering school district, hospital, clinic, or law enforcement agency that will refer potentially eligible families to the community-based organization.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Have received a statement of support for the community-based organization’s participation in the pilot program from the county child welfare agency in each county in which the organization operates.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) Comply with all additional requirements for community-based organizations
					 that will be participating in the pilot program that are imposed by the Office of Child Abuse Prevention, relating to all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(i) Eligibility and needs assessment.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(ii) Family support planning.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(iii) Community and cultural responsiveness.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(iv) Safety monitoring.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(v) Participating in California’s closed-loop, enhanced referral database.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(vi) County partnership.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(vii) Staff training and capacity building.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(viii) Pilot program evaluation.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) The selection of 25 community-based organizations by the Office of Child Abuse Prevention, or its designee, to receive grants to operate community pathway teams and provide related training.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) When selecting community-based organizations to participate in the pilot program, the Office of Child Abuse Prevention shall ensure the selection is geographically and demographically diverse and located throughout California.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) A community pathway pilot site shall be required to comply with all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(i) Receive referrals from schools, hospitals, clinics, and law enforcement agencies of families with children for whom a mandated reporter would not be required to make a report pursuant to Section 11166 of the Penal Code, but that have complex needs
					 or multiple stressors, or who are navigating significant barriers, including, but not limited to, families suffering from poverty and families impacted by mental health, substance use issues, significant illness, or death of one of its members.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(ii) Provide assistance to referred families navigating services related to basic needs, childcare access, behavioral health coordination, financial stability, benefits continuity, and other supports that stabilize families and reduce unnecessary involvement in the child welfare system.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(iii) Participate in a closed-loop referral system to track referrals and document family progress after being connected to services without referral to the child welfare system.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) The training provided by the community-based organization shall include training, support, and incentives for
					 mandated reporters, as defined in Section 11165.7 of the Penal Code, from the entity or entities described in subparagraph (B) of paragraph (1).</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) (A) An evaluation of the pilot program to assess the effectiveness of community-based alternatives to involvement in the child welfare system.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Utilization of a standardized, evidence-informed protective factors assessment tool, or similar assessment tool, and shall collect data elements and outcomes. When collecting data, a participating community-based organization shall not use the child welfare data system.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) The Office of Child Abuse Prevention shall identify uniform data elements to be collected by participating community-based organizations and shall not require a participating community-based organization to provide any personally
					 identifying information relating to families served by a community pathway unit. The Office of Child Abuse Prevention shall also evaluate all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(i) Work plans developed for alternative referrals with partnering agencies.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(ii) Engagement of participating families in supportive services. </div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(iii) Changes in results of the evidence-informed protective factors assessment tool, or similar assessment tool, used by participating community-based organizations.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(iv) Rates of referral of participating families to a child welfare agency.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) The Office of Child Abuse Prevention shall establish an internal unit of at least three staff positions to oversee implementation and consistency
					 of the pilot program and alignment with other initiatives of the State Department of Social Services, including, but not limited to, family first prevention services and systems of care.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(d) The Office of Child Abuse Prevention may contract with a nonprofit organization to do some or all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Develop and implement outreach materials, notice of funding opportunity, and communications to solicit community-based organizations to participate in the pilot program.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Contracting and accounting for the participating community-based organizations.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Compliance monitoring and assistance.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Data collection, review, and reporting.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5) Training, certification, and implementation support for data reporting, program standards, and other identified tools for quality service provision at community pathway teams.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(6) Peer learning and office hours opportunities for participating community-based organizations.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(7) Developing and implementing processes and structures for consistent data collection.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(8) Independent evaluation of the pilot program.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(9) Dissemination of project information and learning.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">18974.1.</h6> (a) Based on the results of the evaluation conducted pursuant to paragraph (3) of subdivision (b) of Section 18974, the Office of Child Abuse Prevention shall prepare a report to the Legislature and provide recommendations for statewide implementation of a community-supporting framework no later than July 1, 2030.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) (1) A report to be submitted pursuant to subdivision (a) shall be submitted in compliance with Section 9795 of the Government Code.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Pursuant to Section 10231.5 of the Government Code, this section is repealed on January 1, 2031.</div></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></body></html>
